<div id=3D"outline-container-orgc94c531" class=3D"outline-4">
<h4 id=3D"orgc94c531">External Types</h4>
<div class=3D"outline-text-4" id=3D"text-orgc94c531">
<p>
When interfacing with foreign function libraries, it is now possible
to define external type
</p>

<div class=3D"org-src-container">
<pre class=3D"src src-ocaml"><code><span style=3D"color: #242521; font-weig=
ht: bold;">type</span> <span style=3D"color: #444fcf; font-weight: bold;">i=
nt_gmp</span> =3D <span style=3D"color: #242521; font-weight: bold;">extern=
al</span> <span style=3D"color: #ca3400;">"mpz_t"</span>
<span style=3D"color: #242521; font-weight: bold;">type</span> <span style=
=3D"color: #444fcf; font-weight: bold;">float_gmp</span> =3D <span style=3D=
"color: #242521; font-weight: bold;">external</span> <span style=3D"color: =
#ca3400;">"mpf_t"</span>
</code></pre>
</div>

<p>
Compared to an abstract type definition, the external type name
"mpz_t" (resp. <code>mpf_t</code>) makes the type distinguishable from any
non-abstract types or external types with a different name.
</p>

<p>
In particular, this makes FFI types better behaved when combined with
Generalised Abstract Data Types (GADTs). For instance, The typechecker
is able to prove that
</p>

<div class=3D"org-src-container">
<pre class=3D"src src-ocaml"><code><span style=3D"color: #242521; font-weig=
ht: bold;">let</span> <span style=3D"color: #a7601f;">ok</span>:<span style=
=3D"color: #444fcf; font-weight: bold;"> (int_gmp,[` </span><span style=3D"=
color: #242521;">A</span><span style=3D"color: #444fcf; font-weight: bold;"=
>] ) </span><span style=3D"color: #557400; font-weight: bold;">Type.</span>=
<span style=3D"color: #444fcf; font-weight: bold;">eq -&gt; _ </span>=3D <s=
pan style=3D"color: #006f00; font-weight: bold;">function</span> <span styl=
e=3D"color: #007a9f;">_</span> -&gt; .
</code></pre>
</div>

<p>
is a total function because the external type <code>int_gmp</code> is not c=
ompatible
with a polymorphic variant type.
</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id=3D"outline-container-org49e3d56" class=3D"outline-4">
<h4 id=3D"org49e3d56">Warning: Abstract types in the current module</h4>
<div class=3D"outline-text-4" id=3D"text-org49e3d56">
<p>
The astute reader has probably noticed in the definition above that,
in OCaml 5.4.0, the typechecker does accept
</p>

<div class=3D"org-src-container">
<pre class=3D"src src-ocaml"><code><span style=3D"color: #242521; font-weig=
ht: bold;">type</span> <span style=3D"color: #444fcf; font-weight: bold;">i=
nt_gmp</span>
<span style=3D"color: #242521; font-weight: bold;">let</span> <span style=
=3D"color: #a7601f;">ok</span>:<span style=3D"color: #444fcf; font-weight: =
bold;"> (int_gmp, [` </span><span style=3D"color: #242521;">A</span><span s=
tyle=3D"color: #444fcf; font-weight: bold;">] ) </span><span style=3D"color=
: #557400; font-weight: bold;">Type.</span><span style=3D"color: #444fcf; f=
ont-weight: bold;">eq -&gt; _ </span>=3D <span style=3D"color: #006f00; fon=
t-weight: bold;">function</span> <span style=3D"color: #007a9f;">_</span> -=
&gt; .
</code></pre>
</div>
<p>
as total.
</p>

<p>
Indeed until OCaml 5.5.0, abstract types defined in the current module
</p>
<div class=3D"org-src-container">
<pre class=3D"src src-ocaml"><code><span style=3D"color: #242521; font-weig=
ht: bold;">type</span> <span style=3D"color: #444fcf; font-weight: bold;">a=
</span>
<span style=3D"color: #242521; font-weight: bold;">type</span> <span style=
=3D"color: #444fcf; font-weight: bold;">b</span>
</code></pre>
</div>

<p>
were considered as unique and provably different
</p>

<div class=3D"org-src-container">
<pre class=3D"src src-ocaml"><code><span style=3D"color: #242521; font-weig=
ht: bold;">let</span> <span style=3D"color: #a7601f;">f</span>:<span style=
=3D"color: #444fcf; font-weight: bold;"> 'x. (a,b) </span><span style=3D"co=
lor: #557400; font-weight: bold;">Type.</span><span style=3D"color: #444fcf=
; font-weight: bold;">eq -&gt; 'x </span>=3D <span style=3D"color: #006f00;=
 font-weight: bold;">function</span> <span style=3D"color: #007a9f;">_</spa=
n> -&gt; .
</code></pre>
</div>

<p>
However, this special rule for local definition of abstract types was
very brittle. As soon as one moved outside of the current module, it
was no longer possible to prove that the types were different.
</p>

<div class=3D"org-src-container">
<pre class=3D"src src-ocaml"><code><span style=3D"color: #242521; font-weig=
ht: bold;">module</span> <span style=3D"color: #557400; font-weight: bold;"=
>M</span> =3D <span style=3D"color: #242521; font-weight: bold;">struct</sp=
an>
  <span style=3D"color: #242521; font-weight: bold;">type</span> <span styl=
e=3D"color: #444fcf; font-weight: bold;">a</span>
  <span style=3D"color: #242521; font-weight: bold;">type</span> <span styl=
e=3D"color: #444fcf; font-weight: bold;">b</span>
<span style=3D"color: #242521; font-weight: bold;">end</span>
<span style=3D"color: #242521; font-weight: bold;">let</span> <span style=
=3D"color: #a7601f;">fail</span>:<span style=3D"color: #444fcf; font-weight=
: bold;"> 'x. (</span><span style=3D"color: #557400; font-weight: bold;">M.=
</span><span style=3D"color: #444fcf; font-weight: bold;">a,</span><span st=
yle=3D"color: #557400; font-weight: bold;">M.</span><span style=3D"color: #=
444fcf; font-weight: bold;">b) </span><span style=3D"color: #557400; font-w=
eight: bold;">Type.</span><span style=3D"color: #444fcf; font-weight: bold;=
">eq -&gt; 'x </span>=3D <span style=3D"color: #006f00; font-weight: bold;"=
>function</span> <span style=3D"color: #007a9f;">_</span> -&gt; .
</code></pre>
</div>
<pre class=3D"example" id=3D"org93e6d9f">
Error: This match case could not be refuted.
       Here is an example of a value that would reach it: Equal
</pre>

<p>
This special typechecking rule has been removed in OCaml 5.5.0. If you were=
 relying on it,
for instance, because you used an abstract type as type-level label in a GA=
DTs, you
can change your abstract type definition to a possibly private abbreviation=
 of a polymorphic variant
</p>

<div class=3D"org-src-container">
<pre class=3D"src src-ocaml"><code><span style=3D"color: #242521; font-weig=
ht: bold;">type</span> <span style=3D"color: #444fcf; font-weight: bold;">a=
